t300.text: It's something I strive for in all in all my designs, & IDGAF if that makes them seem wishy washy or toothless in pushing player behaviour. The player behaviours I'm most interested in promoting is honesty & informed consent.

t301.text: This may or may not be an unpopular opinion, I don't really care. In Impulse Drive, I started trying to write with honesty with each other as a pillar of play & consent as something actively engaged with & not passively assumed.

t302.text: This includes fudging rolls. If a roll threatens to ruin someone's fun, discuss it as a group & reach a decision that you all consent to. Don't leave this up to on player to secretly make decisions on the groups behalf about which rules to ignore.

t303.text: Honest communication with the folks you play with is a cornerstone of building trust, & looking after each other. Let the tension of the unknown be fictional, indulge in dramatic irony, but don't let fear of "spoilers" (UGH) keep you from being honest with each other.

t304.text: SECRETS. GM secrets, player secrets, hidden agendas, all of that. Characters can keep stuff from each other or be unaware of something but no person in the game should.
